{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14227"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14227"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.06,0.74,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6914"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103010"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6914"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14227"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85474"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44207"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103010"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent, complaining of heavy, irregular menstrual bleeding for the past six months. She reports that her periods are unpredictable and last for 10-14 days. She also experiences bleeding between her periods. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale but otherwise well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals no masses or tenderness. A pelvic ultrasound shows normal ovaries and uterus. Hormonal tests, including thyroid function tests, prolactin, and androgen levels, are all within normal ranges.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometriosis","Uterine polyp","Abnormal uterine bleeding due to ovulatory dysfunction (AUB-O)","Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)","Hypothyroidism"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation and investigation results, the most likely diagnosis for this adolescent girl is \u003Cstrong\u003Eabnormal uterine bleeding due to ovulatory dysfunction (AUB-O)\u003C/strong\u003E. AUB-O is a common diagnosis in adolescents who present with heavy, irregular menstrual bleeding, especially when other causes have been ruled out. The patient\u0027s symptoms of unpredictable, prolonged periods and intermenstrual bleeding are characteristic of AUB-O.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause heavy menstrual bleeding, but it typically presents with cyclic pelvic pain, which is not mentioned in this case. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Euterine polyp\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause abnormal bleeding, but it would likely be visible on ultrasound. Moreover, uterine polyps are uncommon in adolescents and typically cause more focal, rather than diffuse, abnormal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)\u003C/strong\u003E can cause menstrual irregularities, but it typically presents with oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea rather than heavy, frequent bleeding. The normal androgen levels and ultrasound findings also make PCOS less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause menstrual irregularities, but the normal thyroid function tests rule out this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in adolescents, AUB is often due to anovulatory cycles resulting from the immaturity of the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis. This can lead to unopposed estrogen stimulation of the endometrium, resulting in heavy, irregular bleeding. The normal ultrasound and hormonal tests do not rule out AUB-O; in fact, they support this diagnosis by excluding other potential causes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abnormal uterine bleeding due to ovulatory dysfunction (AUB-O) is a common diagnosis in adolescents with heavy, irregular menstrual bleeding.","Normal ultrasound and hormonal tests do not rule out abnormal uterine bleeding due to ovulatory dysfunction (AUB-O) in adolescents.","Endometriosis and uterine polyps are less common causes of menorrhagia in adolescents compared to abnormal uterine bleeding due to ovulatory dysfunction (AUB-O)."],"references":["Whitaker L, Critchley HO. Abnormal uterine bleeding. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2016 Jul;34:54-65. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26803558/","Whitaker L, Critchley HO. Abnormal uterine bleeding. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2016 Jul;34:54-65."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85474"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14227"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85474"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-18T11:17:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-18T11:18:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6914"}},"content":